Jan 25 2009 	Great stay in an amazing City	I work for a major internaional airline so we knew that my standards would be high for the accommodation on a mini-break. With Dubai we were also looking at the major problem of there being simply too much choice!! We had decided to visit the city on the basis that it's one of the destinations I have not yet been to as crew and we fancied a bit of shopping (the Dubai Shopping Festival was too tempting an offer for us!!). We were amazed at the volume of 5* hotels and the competitive prices on offer across the city. The Al Murooj Rotana had an offer which meant that it worked out the best price basically - after reading thousands upon thousands of reviews of various hotels on TripAdvisor we just decided that we should go for the cheapest offer for a 5* hotel and hope for the best!!!I was so pleasantly surprised I just can't tell you! The reviews for this hotel seemed completely unfair - most hotels had such a mixture of good and bad reviews that we just decided to ignore them and I'm glad we went with that opinion. I had read comments saying that the staff were unfriendly, facilities not good enough and room service rather useless - but I beg to differ. I must point out that I have been around the block a bit and am clued-up on varying cultures - In case of those who are not aware, and with the greatest respect to the wonderful culture, women in Dubai will not be recognised as, well, relevant??? I have my suspicions that some of the reviews written about any of the hotels in Dubai from dissatisfied customers was possibly due to the way the women are recieved. For example, all of our accommodation, car hire etc was booked by me (the missus), but when trying to sort out the car hire the gentleman serving us was not talking to me (despite it being in my name) but to my other half - the same occurred at the hotel reception. It was funny at times as I was asking questions to staff and they would be answering the question to my other half! This is just the culture - I did not feel uncomfortable, disrespected or maltreated in any way as I respect the fact that this is just the done thing. In the same way, I imagine it's strange for a Muslim woman visiting the UK to have a man look her directly in the eye (seen as disrespectful in their native countries apparently). We found that the staff were so friendly and their attention to details was superb. I stay in 4* hotels around the world on a weekly basis and this hotel was, in my opinion, one of the friendliest and professional I have visited in a long time. The room (we had a non-smoking king room with a balcony) contained everything you would expect - a varied and well-stocked mini-bar (not that I would recommend buying anything from a mini-bar as it's ridiculously expensive!), a good sized bathroom with shower and all the lovely little extras we all need (hairdryer, bathrobe, slippers, shampoo etc) and the room was perfectly lovely - much as any other hotel room is from 4-5* to be frank. The amenities at the hotel were also of a very high standard - the pool and fitness centre were lovely, and the restaurants we visited were very good indeed. We'd particularly recommend the Indian Restaurant and, furthermore, the Amarone on their wine list!!!Before our arrival we had been a little worried about the location of the hotel, being in the middle of the business district, but in fairness it was pretty central to everywhere we wanted to visit (and taxis are very cheap!). There is building work going on all over Dubai but we found that it didn't make a difference to our stay.The one and only small detail I will mention is that we were kept awake one night by a rather noisy room party in the room next to us. This can happen in any hotel and I've had it so many times I can't count (and may have actually been in a few of these said room parties on a few occasions admittedly) so all I will say is that we had a door to adjoin said room to ours for bigger guest parties - it's a bit tricky to soundproof a door so maybe you should check this when you are shown your room!!!We both loved the visit - and, yes, Dubai is a very strange place which people will undoubtedly love or hate! We felt it was like a classy version of Las Vegas! Enjoy your stay!	
